segments.text: The student body.
Describe the student body.
Who was here?
What kind of students, people, where were they from?
What was their tip?
What was their basic attitude about life and so forth?
Oh, I don't think it's a lot different now than it was then.
To me, the biggest entrepreneur in the world, right?
All kinds of opportunities.
Is it chicken or egg?
Were they that way before they got to A&M?
I don't think so.
You think A&M?
Not necessarily.
Part of it could be.
What is it at A&M that caused that, that generates that?
There again, I go back to the court.
And I don't know how you could say that would cause it today, since it's such a small part of the body.
But he's still a very big part of it.
But I don't really have a good answer.
Just a spirit.
But you don't get anywhere else.
And many muster his life.
What are the factors that youth can think of that contribute to that spirit?
I guess the fact that you probably have a place in life that you wouldn't have if you hadn't been a part of the university.
And it's such that
It's a very real thing.
And it's displayed in many ways.
And it's probably not even recognized as such by anyone else around.
points in life.

Not at all.

Those were important.
Let's jump on that a second.

Oh, just like any other.

Just like any other.

No.

you were aware of?

I really don't know.
Well, I'm certain it was a national company in Mexico or something up here in the United States.
I'm sure they could put it down there.
And I'm sure over there, particularly in Saudi Arabia, it was around the coast, some of the bigger oil companies were trying to get some natives over there trained.
Were they non-reg or were they in the Corps?
No, they were not.
that I know of.

No.

Oh, yeah.

Korean War.

Oh, there's no question I was going to be on active duty.
When I signed the contract, I signed on for two years active duty, six years inactive.
So, you know, I had an eight-year delay.
It ends up I'm having to be a Cold War veteran, but I could have been a very hot one very quickly.
I went out to find out what petroleum was needed and I was able to do that for a year and a half after I got out of university.
So before I didn't go in until like 1956 and came back out in 1958,
What world event, world or national events, do you remember happening while you were an undergraduate that seemed to you very significant to you?
I think I bought a green one because we had several plans .

Were there any...
important visitors to the campus, notable individuals who came to speak?
Not like we have.

Such as?

No, but where was the dance, where were the dances held?
At Sabisa.

Just like they should.
Just like you'd expect.

Telling bad jokes, using bad language,
What did, what drinking, what did drinking mean?
If somebody was going to be drinking, what were they drinking?
Well, okay, let's say it's a freshman year.
The first, the first time in a lot that a guy has ever hit you.
And if people were smoking, what were they smoking?
What?
What did y'all know about other than tobacco of some sort?
Driving fast, telling bad jokes, chasing girls, and only bumpkins chewed tobacco.
Country, you know, country.
Unless you played baseball.
Oh yeah, that was different.
Of course you can't do that now.
Let's see.
These dances.

Every number?
Could a guy go without a date and cut in?

Okay, sure.

Some people, no.
Yeah, didn't do it with strangers?
No.
But she didn't come all the way down for, you know, being humiliated.

How big did y'all think it was when it was finished?
Was your commencement held there?
Please describe...
The biggest difference I've seen now is in the commission ceremony.
We had several hundred getting commissions.
Now it's just a handful.
I don't need to go take a look.
It's amazing.
I didn't know that.
Describe commissioning and commencement was on the same day?
On the same day.
Describe that day.
Who was there?
Oh, of course, my parents and my wife.
Probably my sister.
Probably, yeah.
Was there a, do you even remember who the speaker was?
Was it somebody of the?
No, but I tell you, I remember one of the things.
I had the opportunity to get the speaker for our senior, our senior base.
And you're inferring that when he got through, y'all did wonder why you'd ask.
The senior and the senior band, who went to the senior banquet?
Was this for dates, or was it only the seniors?
Dates.
And at commencement, name was called, everybody, hands were shaking.
So what kind of?
That you had cleared all your courses?

There's all those labs.

I remember a lot with the technical chemistry, some of the more basic geology courses.
Some of those were the slowest.
But speaking of the others, the last two or three years, we've had only probably 15 problems, and normally probably 25 or 30.

Let's see.
We talked about some of John's.

No.

Never had a car.

Actually, the last three years.

And here were all kinds of questions.

girlfriend had to get a date.

Bupo.

Let's see.
Colonel Davis was the commandant.

student organizations what was the most prestigious undergraduate student position office if you could have been anything on campus we really didn't have a

Student Corps.

Members?

hanging.

's was to get their members elected.

Oh.

No.

Hitchhiking?

All very, very hard.
